# mojo-jit-crash-retry Skill History

## v4.1.0 (2026-05-09)

**Changed by:** ProjectOdyssey PR #5363/#5364 forensic investigation of Mojo 1.0.0b2 KGEN crash
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- **MINOR bump (4.0.0 → 4.1.0):** Added "libKGEN Stripped-Binary Crash Forensics" section
  documenting the dynsym + objdump procedure
- New section explains why the published 3-frame trace is the Crashpad signal-handler
  chain (NOT the actual fault), and what frame patterns mean (`call backtrace@plt`,
  function-pointer dispatch, `__fortify_fail_abort` at libc +0x45330)
- Documents the `_ZNSt24uniform_int_distributionImEclISt13random_deviceEEmRT_RKNS0_10param_typeE@@Base`
  anchor symbol that fronts a 60+KB stripped region of folded-out internal functions
- Documents cross-version offset comparison: bucketing into the same anchor symbol is a
  STRONG match signal even when absolute offsets differ by KB across Mojo rebuilds
- Cross-references three companion skills: `gha-mojo-coredump-capture` (needed because
  frame 4 is unreachable from the published trace), `mojo-binary-closed-source-debugging`
  (why you can't build Mojo from source to step through it), `mojo-sanitizer-support-matrix`
  (which sanitizers actually work in 1.0.0b2)
- Added 2 Failed Attempts rows: treating Crashpad frames as the real stack; reading
  absolute offset differences as different bugs
- Description trigger list extended with conditions 20-22

### Why

The v4.0.0 4-hypothesis disproof methodology established WHAT the crash isn't. v4.1.0
documents the forensic procedure that produced the analysis shared with upstream: how to
decode the stripped libKGEN trace, why the printed frames are useless, and how to
fingerprint defects across Mojo versions. Reproducible on any Mojo 1.0.0b2 install.

### Outstanding (carry into v4.2.0+ amendments)

- Once a coredump is captured via `gha-mojo-coredump-capture` on PR #5364, document the
  actual frame 4 contents and amend with the resolved root cause

